      "id": "ae012038fc3d4692",
      "text": "**No**, \"ein Fortschritt\" translates to \"a progress\" or \"an advancement\" in English. It refers to a move forward, an improvement, or an increase in development. It does not necessarily mean \"one step of progress.\""
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "fe5425a1377854d0",
      "text": "[…]"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "4be863be546af2b6",
      "text": "This passage is a complex philosophical argument that seems to be making the point that writing and rereading what has been written is not an additional effort, but rather a liberation and fruitful use of mental faculties that are already at work. It argues that if we don't write, we waste our strength and don't make progress. The use of the term \"Fortschritt\" in this context reinforces this idea by suggesting that writing and rereading leads to a forward movement or an advancement. The passage appears to be drawing on the idea that [[Language]] and [[Communication]] (represented by the term \"Logos\") are crucial to human understanding and that directing our mental faculties towards this space of intersubjective understanding is an important aspect of our spiritual lives. Overall, the passage presents a strong argument for the value of writing and rereading."
