      "type": "add",
      "item": {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "86225f4559c452db",
        "text": "What does writing mean? [⇒ [[Schreiben]]] In any case, it is not an additional effort that one does not have to make in a non-writing state, just as one who is not a mountain climber is relieved of the effort of climbing. It is rather only the orientation of the ordinary mental faculty towards a certain space in which it becomes communicable. I speak of space because I once heard someone refer to logos as space, as the \"space of intersubjective understanding.\" And didn't Heraclitus also call the logos that which is common to all? Thus, the activity of the mind is to be directed towards it. This is, as I said, no additional effort, it is only the liberation, fruitfulness of forces that are already at work. We think anyway, we have to cope with our life spiritually anyway. But if we don't write, we waste our strength, we move in circles, we don't get ahead. Writing and rereading what we have written make it possible to continue to write.\n"
      },
